# Metadata Generation Rules

## Core principles

- Generate titles and metas from **onboarding brief data**, not URL alone.
- Prioritize business goals, services, audience, and conversion intent.
- Use **page type** to determine structure.
- Suggest **low-barrier, high-opportunity** keywords (long-tail, service-specific first).
- Always surface **3 keyword options** each with reasoning.
- **Never auto-apply** metadata without explicit user confirmation in the UI.

## Page type title patterns (targets)

- **Homepage:** `[Brand] | [Core Service] & [Outcome]`
- **Service:** `[Service] | [Brand] - [Location if local]`
- **Location:** `[Service] [Location] | [Brand]`
- **Blog:** `[Question/Topic] | [Brand]`
- **About:** `[Brand] | [Trust Signal]`

Implementations may shorten for length limits; keep the same intent order.

## Local vs national

- **Local-first:** Include city/metro in title and meta where it reads naturally.
- **Regional:** Mention service area without stuffing.
- **National:** Location optional; emphasize service + outcome.
- **Dual focus:** Local in visible copy; national reach in intent (no contradictory claims).

## Keyword selection (priority order)

1. Service-specific long-tail.
2. Local service phrases if local-first.
3. Question-based for blog/support.
4. Branded service terms.
5. Avoid high-competition head terms unless brief explicitly seeds them.

## Implementation alignment

- Keep logic **deterministic** and **explainable** (no black-box scoring).
- **Do not** persist keywords from suggestions unless the product explicitly adds storage later; titles/meta apply only via an explicit apply action.
